  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Ritual Text for the Mid-Yuan Festival at the Hall of Divine Presence
  author: Jung Po
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Offering

    Your descent shines with majesty—
    who can fathom the immeasurable divine?
    When sincerity reaches toward Heaven,
    sometimes the lofty ears are moved to listen.
    I humbly pray you cast your gaze below
    and bestow your grace upon my devotion.

    Second Offering

    Heaven's watchfulness knows no barrier,
    truly responding to the prayers of multitudes.
    Should sincere hearts grow ever more fervent,
    how could such reverence be deemed a violation?
    Receive these offerings with favor,
    and grant us harvests in abundance.

    Third Offering

    Sun and moon hold not their stations,
    and we have arrived at Mid-Yuan's season.
    Heaven and earth share no distance—
    through a single thought, perhaps we touch.
    I bow in reflection:
    though I wear the throne, my virtue falls short.
    Though a ruler's court may be fitting,
    I fear the journey from which I cannot return.
    Fortune and misfortune, regret and worry—
    all arise from the stirring of action.
    Let purification and ritual fasting make the offering true,
    that lasting blessing may endure.

    Now, as the celestial immortals assess and compare,
    I respectfully send forth prayers across a thousand leagues.
    How could I, so humble and insignificant,
    claim alone the honor and glory?
    Rather, with all the people,
    may we together attain peace and tranquility.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mid-Yuan refers to the 15th day of the 7th lunar month, a traditional festival for honoring celestial and earthly powers
  - key: ''
    value: The three offerings (First, Second, Third) represent the traditional structure of ritual presentations in East Asian ceremonial practice
  - key: ''
    value: The 'immortals assessing and comparing' alludes to the celestial examination of human virtue and conduct
